        "id": "q02-01",
        "question": "A model trained to identify pneumonia on chest X-rays using labeled examples of 'pneumonia' and 'no pneumonia' is an example of:",
        "options": [
          "Unsupervised learning",
          "Reinforcement learning",
          "Supervised learning",
          "Transfer learning"
        ],
        "correct": 2,
        "explanation": "Supervised learning uses labeled examples (input + correct output) to train a model. The labeled X-rays with diagnosis labels are the supervised training signal."
      },
      {
        "id": "q02-02",
        "question": "A vendor reports their AI tool has 95% accuracy for detecting a cancer that occurs in 2% of screened patients. What is the most important follow-up question?",
        "options": [
          "What is the model's AUC score?",
          "What are the sensitivity and positive predictive value?",
          "How many patients were in the test set?",
          "Is the model FDA approved?"
        ],
        "correct": 1,
        "explanation": "With a 2% disease prevalence, 95% accuracy could be achieved by simply predicting 'no cancer' for every patient. Sensitivity (does it catch actual cancers?) and PPV (when it flags cancer, is it right?) are far more informative than raw accuracy in imbalanced datasets."
      },
      {
        "id": "q02-03",
        "question": "What is 'data leakage' in the context of ML model evaluation?",
        "options": [
          "When patient data is accidentally shared with unauthorized parties",
          "When information from the test set influences the training process",
          "When the model's predictions are leaked to the public before publication",
          "When training data is corrupted by missing values"
        ],
        "correct": 1,
        "explanation": "Data leakage occurs when test data information contaminates training, artificially inflating performance metrics. A common example: the same patient appearing in both training and test sets."
      },
      {
        "id": "q02-04",
        "question": "In a cancer screening application, you would prioritize which metric?",
        "options": [
          "High specificity (minimize false positives)",
          "High sensitivity (minimize missed cancers)",
          "High accuracy (maximize overall correct predictions)",
          "High F1 score (balance precision and recall)"
        ],
        "correct": 1,
        "explanation": "In screening, the priority is not missing true cases (high sensitivity). A missed cancer has far worse consequences than a false alarm that leads to additional workup. The threshold should be set to maximize sensitivity, accepting some reduction in specificity."
      },
      {
        "id": "q02-05",
        "question": "A model achieves 99% accuracy on training data but only 60% on test data. This is most likely caused by:",
        "options": [
          "Insufficient training data",
          "Overfitting — the model memorized training examples",
          "An error in the model architecture",
          "Biased test data"
        ],
        "correct": 1,
        "explanation": "A large gap between training and test performance is the hallmark of overfitting. The model learned to memorize training examples rather than discover generalizable patterns."
      }
